            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Elias Kadoorie\u2019s story is one of quiet preservation, a life dedicated to mending the fractured histories of objects. Born in London to Iraqi-Jewish parents who had fled Baghdad in the 1960s, Elias grew up in a home filled with the ghosts of a lost world. His most treasured possession was his grandfather's intricately carved backgammon board, one of the few heirlooms his family managed to bring with them. Tracing its geometric patterns, he developed a profound appreciation for the stories and craftsmanship embedded in things that survive transit and time.\n\nThis fascination led him to pursue a Bachelor's degree in Art History, but he found academia too detached. He craved a tactile connection to the past, which he discovered in a demanding apprenticeship with a furniture restorer in Clerkenwell. He learned the patient arts of French polishing, veneer repair, and gold leaf application. Twenty years ago, a specialized job restoring lacquered screens for a prominent collector brought him to San Francisco, a city whose fog and layered history reminded him of a cooler, more eccentric London. When his employer retired, Elias took a leap of faith and opened his own small workshop, \"Kadoorie Restoration,\" a stone's throw from his North Beach apartment.\n\nHis daily routine is a ritual of deliberateness. A morning walk takes him past the scent of espresso and baking bread to his studio, a haven of wood polish and focused silence. He is a solitary figure but not a lonely one; his relationships are with his clients, the local bookstore owner, and the objects themselves, whose secrets he coaxes out with gentle hands. A long-term relationship ended amicably five years ago, leaving him with a quiet, contemplative independence he has come to cherish.\n\nElias\u2019s connection to San Francisco is rooted in his craft. He sees himself as a caretaker of the city's small, forgotten histories\u2014repairing a Victorian settee from a Pacific Heights mansion or a steamer trunk that crossed the Pacific. His dream is not of wealth, but of legacy. He hopes one day to be entrusted with restoring a significant piece of Mizrahi heritage, a tangible link to his own origins. More pressingly, he aspires to find a dedicated apprentice, someone to whom he can pass on his meticulous skills, ensuring the art of restoration, like the objects he loves, endures."
